      w.appendChild(el('p', {}, 'For a unity-feedback loop with forward transfer function K*G(s) = K*N(s)/D(s), the closed-loop poles are the roots of the characteristic equation D(s) + K*N(s) = 0. As K varies from 0 to infinity, these roots trace continuous curves called the root locus. At K=0 the closed-loop poles coincide with the open-loop poles (roots of D); as K grows they migrate toward the open-loop zeros (roots of N) or off to infinity along asymptotes.'));
      w.appendChild(el('div', { 'class': 'cs-eq' }, 'Characteristic eqn:  1 + K*G(s) = 0\n=>  D(s) + K*N(s) = 0\n\nStart (K=0):  poles = roots of D(s)\nEnd  (K=inf): poles -> zeros of N(s), rest to infinity\nNo. of asymptotes = (#poles - #zeros)\nAsymptote angles = (2q+1)*180 / (P - Z) degrees'));
      w.appendChild(el('p', {}, 'Here, for every gain K on the sweep we form the real polynomial D(s)+K*N(s) and solve it numerically (Durand-Kerner). Plotting the roots for hundreds of K values reproduces the exact locus. Where a branch crosses the imaginary axis, the closed loop is marginally stable; the corresponding K is the critical gain.'));
