      'Conclude stability when Z = 0; otherwise Z gives the number of unstable closed-loop poles.'],
    refs: ['Nyquist, H. "Regeneration Theory", Bell System Tech. J., 1932.',
      'Nise, "Control Systems Engineering", Ch. 10.',
      'Ogata, "Modern Control Engineering", Ch. 7.'],
    quiz: [
      { q: 'In the Nyquist criterion Z = N + P, stability requires:', opts: ['Z = 0', 'N = 0 always', 'P = 0 always', 'Z = P'], correct: 0, exp: 'Z is the count of closed-loop RHP poles; the loop is stable iff Z = 0.' },
      { q: 'For an open-loop-stable system (P = 0), the loop is stable if the Nyquist locus:', opts: ['Encircles -1 once', 'Does not encircle the point -1+j0', 'Passes through the origin', 'Crosses +1'], correct: 1, exp: 'With P=0, stability needs N=0, i.e. no encirclements of the critical point -1.' },
      { q: 'The critical point in the Nyquist plane is at:', opts: ['(0, 0)', '(+1, 0)', '(-1, 0)', '(0, -1)'], correct: 2, exp: 'It is -1+j0, arising from 1 + G(jw) = 0 at the loop characteristic equation.' },
      { q: 'A clockwise encirclement of -1 contributes to N as:', opts: ['-1', '+1', '0', '+2'], correct: 1, exp: 'Clockwise encirclements count as positive N; counter-clockwise as negative.' }
