    name: 'Routh-Hurwitz criterion',
    aim: 'Enter the coefficients of a characteristic polynomial, build the Routh array, and determine stability from the sign of the first column — with the number of right-half-plane roots equal to the number of sign changes.',
    theory: function () {
      var w = el('div');
      w.appendChild(el('p', {}, 'The Routh-Hurwitz criterion decides stability of a polynomial without finding its roots. For a(s) = a0 s^n + a1 s^(n-1) + ... + an, all roots lie in the open left-half plane (the system is stable) if and only if every entry in the first column of the Routh array is non-zero and of the same sign. The number of sign changes in the first column equals the number of roots with positive real part. The array is built row by row from determinant-like combinations of the rows above.'));
      w.appendChild(el('div', { 'class': 'cs-eq' }, 'a(s) = a0 s^n + a1 s^(n-1) + ... + an\n\nRow s^n   :  a0   a2   a4  ...\nRow s^(n-1):  a1   a3   a5  ...\nRow s^(n-2):  b1   b2  ...  where  b1 = (a1*a2 - a0*a3)/a1\n\nStable  <=>  no sign change in first column\nsign changes  =  number of RHP roots'));
      w.appendChild(el('p', {}, 'Special cases are handled: a zero in the first column (with a non-zero rest of the row) is replaced by a small epsilon; a row of all zeros is reconstructed from the auxiliary polynomial’s derivative, which also flags poles on the imaginary axis (marginal stability).'));
